ğŸ”° What is ORM?

ORM (Object-Relational Mapping) is a technique that maps objects in code to rows in a relational database.
Java class âŸ¶ Table
Java field âŸ¶ Column
Java object âŸ¶ Row in the table
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ğŸ”§ Tools in Java for ORM
The most popular Java ORM framework is Hibernate. Other examples include:

JPA (Java Persistence API â€“ specification)

EclipseLink

MyBatis (semi-ORM)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ… Step 1: Simple Example â€“ One Entity, One Table

ğŸ¯ Table in Database:
CREATE TABLE users (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(100),
    email VARCHAR(100)
);

ğŸ§‘ Java Class with ORM Mapping (JPA + Hibernate):
import jakarta.persistence.*;

@Entity
@Table(name = "users")
public class User {

    @Id
    private int id;

    private String name;

    private String email;

    // Constructors, Getters, Setters
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
User user = new User();
user.setId(1);
user.setName("Alice");
user.setEmail("alice@example.com");

// Hibernate will map this object to an INSERT query
session.save(user);

â¡ï¸ The object gets inserted as a row into the users table.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ… Step 2: Adding Relationships (One-to-Many)

Now let's say one User has many Orders.
ğŸ¯ Tables:
CREATE TABLE orders (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    item_name VARCHAR(100),
    user_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id)
);

ğŸ§‘ Java Entity â€“ Order:
@Entity
@Table(name = "orders")
public class Order {

    @Id
    private int id;

    private String itemName;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id")
    private User user;

    // Getters and setters
}


ğŸ§‘ Java Entity â€“ updated User:
@Entity
@Table(name = "users")
public class User {

    @Id
    private int id;

    private String name;

    private String email;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user")
    private List<Order> orders;

    // Getters and setters
}

â¡ï¸ Hibernate now handles foreign key relationships automatically.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ… Step 3: Many-to-Many Relationships
Letâ€™s say a Student can enroll in many Courses, and a Course can have many Students.

ğŸ¯ Tables:
CREATE TABLE students (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(100)
);

CREATE TABLE courses (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    title VARCHAR(100)
);

CREATE TABLE student_course (
    student_id INT,
    course_id INT,
    PRIMARY KEY (student_id, course_id),
    FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students(id),
    FOREIGN KEY (course_id) REFERENCES courses(id)
);


ğŸ§‘ Java Entity â€“ Student:
@Entity
@Table(name = "students")
public class Student {

    @Id
    private int id;

    private String name;

    @ManyToMany
    @JoinTable(
        name = "student_course",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id"),
        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
    )
    private List<Course> courses;

    // Getters and setters
}


ğŸ§‘ Java Entity â€“ Course:
@Entity
@Table(name = "courses")
public class Course {

    @Id
    private int id;

    private String title;

    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "courses")
    private List<Student> students;

    // Getters and setters
}
â¡ï¸ Hibernate will manage the join table student_course automatically.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ… ORM Summary Table

| Java Concept          | Database Concept       |
| --------------                 | -------------------                |
| `@Entity`                | Table                                  |
| Class field             | Column                              |
| `@Id`                           | Primary key                   |
| `@OneToMany`        | Foreign key                   |
| `@ManyToMany`     | Join table                      |
| `@Inheritance`  | Table per hierarchy |

